You use the proofs to recursively verify that a given computation lead to the new state, by feeding it with some private data (the list of signatures) - the proof is always accompanied by a public state (that public state could include a list of eligible signer keys, and a nullifier to prevent double-signing, for example). So you would feed your signatures into the ZkProgram and check 1) are the public keys valid (member of a merkle tree, if thats something you want to check) 2) verify the signature 3) constrain the result to the public input 


```ts

// for each i

let currentPublicKey = listOfKeys[i];
let payload = listOfPayloads[i];
let sig = listOfSigs[i];

// verify public key is within a list, if needed
sig.verify(payload, currentPublicKey);

// these two steps below are important to "constrain" the correctness of the calculating to the public input
publicInput[i].publicKey.assertEqual(currentPublicKey);
publicInput[i].payload.assertEqual(payload);

```
